  "time_ut": 1658772706,
  "original_lang": "ta",
  "original_title": "\u2019\u0b9a\u0bc6\u0baa\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bc6\u0bae\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bb0\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0b87\u0bb2\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc8\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc1 \u0baa\u0bc1\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0baf\u0ba4\u0bca\u0bb0\u0bc1 \u0ba8\u0bc6\u0bb0\u0bc1\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0b9f\u0bbf\u2019",
  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "'A new crisis for Sri Lanka in September'",
      "author": "unknown",
      "body_lines": [
        "The UN Human Rights Council's September session will focus on the government's brutal attack on protesters in front of the presidential secretariat. The executive director of the Center for Alternative Policy, Kalanithi Bhakyasothy Saravanamuthu, said that there will be a further crisis regarding Sri Lanka's human rights violations.",
        "A new resolution on Sri Lanka will be introduced at the September session of the United Nations Human Rights Council. Or there are possibilities to continue with the current motion, he said.",
        "During this, the current situation in Sri Lanka will definitely be discussed. Today, various countries have expressed their displeasure over the government's brutal attack on anti-vacation protesters in particular.",
        "Embassies have issued condemnations. Therefore, there will be a further crisis regarding Sri Lanka's human rights violations.",
        "When Ranil Wickremesinghe came to power, he had the support of various countries. It was believed to have the potential to establish democracy. However, such human rights violations have belied the faith in him.",
        "It is their right to carry out peaceful protests. The move to prevent it by attack is the worst. It can never be accepted.",
        "In the current state of crisis, whether it is the government or the members of parliament, they do not want to go to the polls. They know that if they face the election like that, many people will be rejected by the people. Therefore, he said, he expects the government to start any programs through the IMF and then think about the elections."
      ],
